            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Doesn't this clarify the association with floating windows?\r\n\r\nIt *can* be related to a floating window position, but it *doesn't have to*. It is possible to implement it via `echo`, inline extmark, text in virtual line, statusline, etc.\r\n\r\n> As I understand it, `vim.ui.input` is simply a UI component provided as an interface so that plugins can reimplement it by overriding.\r\n\r\nIt is. Yet `opts.scope` can be used not only for UI decisions. Some example:\r\n- Incorporate it when computing history and/or completion candidates.\r\n- If there is no `opts.default`, auto populate input area with the latest history input from the same scope.\r\n\r\nIn both cases the sentence \"suggest history entry that had the same input scope\" sounds clearer than \"suggest history entry that had the same relative input\".\r\n\r\n> This is fundamentally different from the `scope` in `vim.diagnostic.Opts.Float`. In that case, `scope` determines the range of diagnostics to be displayed in a newly opened floating window ...\r\n\r\nIt is not fundamentally different. As explained above, `opts.scope` can also be reasonably used for something else than UI decisions. And in a way similar to how it is used in `vim.diagnostic.Opts.Float`.",
            "commit_id": "c98fc55d3fc81af2fc3e0bb9b727ebbafc726dd4",
            "created_at": "2026-05-03T10:45:24Z",
            "diff_hunk": "@@ -5129,6 +5130,11 @@ vim.ui.input({opts}, {on_confirm})                            *vim.ui.input()*\n                       • {highlight}? (`function`) Function that will be used\n                         for highlighting user inputs.\n                       • {prompt}? (`string`) Text of the prompt\n+                      • {scope}?",
